## 1. Background & context
Why this module now; what exists today it relates to (other modules/subsystems); constraints from the
current architecture.

## 2. Goals & non-goals
- **Goals** — the outcomes this module must achieve.
- **Non-goals** — explicitly out of scope (so scope doesn't creep). See also the final section.

## 3. Users & roles
Who uses it and what each can do. Note any new roles or role-scoped access this module introduces, and
how they map onto the project's existing permission model.

## 4. Functional requirements
The core of the FRD. Numbered so we can reference them.
- **FR-1** — …
- **FR-2** — …

## 5. Data model (high level)
Entities, key fields, and relationships — enough to plan a schema later (real DDL + access control
comes in the plan / DB-change step). Note links to existing tables/entities.

| Entity | Key fields | Relationships |
|--------|-----------|---------------|
| … | … | … |

## 6. Permissions & security
Who can read/write what; access-control expectations; any sensitive data (PII, financial) and where it
must live. Mirror the project's defense-in-depth model.

## 7. Screens & UX
The screens/flows this needs (list + one line each) and key user journeys. Reuse existing UI patterns
(pagination, empty states, feedback, navigation).

## 8. Business rules
Rules that must always hold (validation, calculations, state transitions). Be explicit — these become tests.

## 9. Integrations & dependencies
Other modules this depends on or feeds; any external services.

## 10. Acceptance criteria
Concrete, checkable "done" statements that guide the plan's verification.
- [ ] …

## 11. Reporting / analytics (if any)
What needs to be summarized, exported, or surfaced.

## 12. Open questions
The discussion list — every unresolved decision. Resolve these to move Draft → In Review → Approved.
- [ ] …

## 13. Out of scope / future
Deliberately deferred — captured so it isn't forgotten.

